## Plan: Add Pagination to `GET /users`

### What I found

The codebase is a small Express + TypeScript API with:
- **`src/routes.ts`** — the only file needing a change; the `GET /users` handler is currently 1 line: `res.json(users)`
- **`src/data.ts`** — 15 hardcoded users (the dataset that drives all pagination math)
- **`tests/routes.test.ts`** — tests are **already written** and define the exact contract

### Exact change: `src/routes.ts` lines 7–9

Replace the current handler body with:

```typescript
router.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  const page  = parseInt(req.query.page  as string, 10) || 1;
  const limit = parseInt(req.query.limit as string, 10) || 10;
  const total      = users.length;
  const totalPages = Math.ceil(total / limit);
  const offset     = (page - 1) * limit;
  const data       = users.slice(offset, offset + limit);

  res.json({
    data,
    pagination: { page, limit, total, totalPages },
  });
});
```

### How every test passes

| Test | Query | offset | data.length | Result |
|------|-------|--------|-------------|--------|
| Default | (none) | 0 | 10 | page=1, limit=10, total=15, totalPages=2 ✓ |
| Second page | `page=2&limit=10` | 10 | 5 | page=2, 5 users ✓ |
| Custom limit | `limit=5` | 0 | 5 | totalPages=3 ✓ |
| Out-of-range | `page=100` | 990 | 0 | `data=[]`, HTTP 200 ✓ |

`Array.slice` naturally returns `[]` when the offset exceeds array length — no special-case needed for out-of-range pages.

### No other files need to change
- No new utility files needed (logic is simple enough inline)
- `src/types.ts`, `src/data.ts`, `src/app.ts`, and `tests/routes.test.ts` are all untouched

